title: Introduction to pvEBayes
text: Contemporary drug postmarketing surveillance largely relies collection spontaneous reports suspected adverse drug events pharmaceutical companies, healthcare professionals, patients. reports curated stored spontaneous reporting systems (SRS), usually organized large frequency table downstream data analysis. consider SRS dataset cataloging AE reports II AE rows across JJ drug columns. Let NijN_{ij} denote number reported cases ii-th AE jj-th drug, =1,...,Ii = 1,..., j=1,...,Jj = 1,..., J. Therefore, AE-drug pairwise occurrences AE-reports summarized ×JI \times J contingency table, (,j)(,j)-th cell catalogs observed count NijN_{ij} indicating number cases involving ii-th AE jj-th drug. Current disproportionality analysis mainly focuses signal detection seeks determine whether observation NijN_{ij} substantially greater corresponding null baseline EijE_{ij}. Poisson model, say, signal strength λij\lambda_{ij} significantly greater 1. addition signal detection, Tan et al. (Stat. Med., 2025) broaden role disproportionality signal estimation. use flexible non-parametric empirical Bayes models enables nuanced empirical Bayes posterior inference (signal strength λ\lambda estimation uncertainty quantification). allows researchers distinguish AE-drug pairs appear similar binary signal detection framework. example, AE-drug pairs signal strengths 1.5 4.0 significantly greater 1 detected signal. differences signal strength may distinct implications medical clinical contexts. Methods implemented package assumes observed count NijN_{ij} conditional EijE_{ij} Nij∣Eij∼Poisson(Eijλij),\begin{equation} \label{eqn:model-poisson-likelihood} N_{ij} \mid E_{ij} \sim \operatorname{Poisson}(E_{ij}\lambda_{ij}),   \end{equation} parameter λij≥0\lambda_{ij} \geq 0 relative reporting ratio, signal strength, (,j)(, j)-th pair measuring ratio actual expected count arising due dependence null baseline expected count. Therefore, {λij}\{\lambda_{ij}\} key parameters interest. large λij\lambda_{ij} indicates strong association drug AE. Let gg prior density function signal strength parameters AE-drug pairs: λij∼g\lambda_{ij} \sim g. , context Poisson model, marginal probability mass function NijN_{ij} given : p(Nij)=∫0∞g(λij)fpois(Nij∣λijEij)dλij, p(N_{ij}) = \int_0^{\infty} g(\lambda_{ij}) \ f_{\text{pois}}(N_{ij} \mid \lambda_{ij}E_{ij}) \ d\lambda_{ij},  fpois(N∣λ)f_{\text{pois}}(N \mid \lambda) probability mass function Poisson random variable mean λ\lambda evaluated NN. empirical Bayes framework, prior distribution consequently estimated data maximizing log marginal likelihood: ĝ=argmaxg∑=1I∑j=1Jlogp(Nij). \hat g = \mathop{\arg \max}\limits_{g} \sum_{=1}^\sum_{j=1}^J \log p(N_{ij}).  , estimated posterior density λ\lambda given NijN_{ij} : p̂(λ∣Nij)=ĝ(λ)fpois(Nij∣λEij)p̂(Nij), \hat{\text{p}}(\lambda \mid N_{ij}) = \frac{\hat g(\lambda) f_{\text{pois}}(N_{ij} \mid \lambda E_{ij})}{\hat{\text{p}}(N_{ij})},  p̂(Nij)=∫0∞ĝ(λij)fpois(Nij∣λijEij)dλij\hat{\text{p}}(N_{ij}) = \int_0^{\infty} \hat g(\lambda_{ij})f_{\text{pois}}(N_{ij}\mid \lambda_{ij}E_{ij}) \ d\lambda_{ij}. empirical Bayes models implemented ‘pvEBayes’ share structure described ; differ assumptions prior distribution. Implemented methods include Gamma-Poisson Shrinker (GPS), Koenker-Mizera (KM) method, Efron’s nonparametric empirical Bayes approach, K-gamma model, general-gamma model. selection prior distribution critical Bayesian analysis. GPS model uses gamma mixture prior assuming signal/non-signal structure SRS data. However, real-world setting, signal strengths (λij){(\lambda_{ij})} often heterogeneous thus follows multi-modal distribution, making difficult assume parametric prior. Non-parametric empirical Bayes models (KM, Efron, K-gamma general-gamma) address challenge utilizing flexible prior general mixture form estimating prior distribution data-driven way. KM method existing implementation REBayes package, relies Mosek, commercial convex optimization solver, may limit accessibility due licensing issues. pvEBayes package provides alternative fully open-source implementation KM method using CVXR. Efron’s method also general nonparametric empirical Bayes implementation deconvolveR package; however, implementation support exposure offset parameter Poisson model, corresponds expected null value Eij{E_{ij}}. pvEBayes, implementation Efron’s method adapted modified deconvolveR support Eij{E_{ij}} Poisson model. addition, package implements novel bi-level Expectation Conditional Maximization (ECM) algorithm proposed Tan et al. (2025) efficient parameter estimation gamma mixture prior based models mentioned . Package ‘pvEBayes’ provides suite streamlined tools effectively fitting models spontaneous reporting system (SRS) frequency tables, extracting summaries, performing hyperparameter tuning, generating graphical summaries (eye plots heatmaps) signal detection estimation. following provide example, borrowed Tan et al. (arxiv, 2025), SRS data analyzing ‘pvEBayes’.

title: Empirical Bayes Methods for Pharmacovigilance
text: pvEBayes R package implements suite nonparametric empirical Bayes methods pharmacovigilance, including Gamma-Poisson Shrinker (GPS), K-gamma, general-gamma, Koenker-Mizera (KM), Efron models. provides tools fitting models spontaneous reporting system (SRS) frequency tables, extracting summaries, performing hyperparameter tuning, generating graphical summaries (eye plots heatmaps) signal detection estimation. Spontaneous Reporting System (SRS) Table: drug safety SRS dataset catalogs AE reports AE rows across J drug columns. Let Nij{N_{ij}} denote number reported cases -th AE j-th drug, =1,...,{= 1,..., } j=1,...,J{j = 1,..., J}. Empirical Bayes modeling disproportionality analysis: Model AE-drug count Nij∼Poisson(λijEij)N_{ij} \sim \text{Poisson}(\lambda_{ij} E_{ij}). EijE_{ij}: expected baseline value assuming AE-drug association. λij>0\lambda_{ij} > 0: relative reporting ratio / signal strength (,j)-th AE-drug pair (multiplicative deviation null baseline value). signal detection signal estimation Traditional disproportionality analysis emphasizes signal detection: identify AE-drug pairs observed counts substantially larger null value, .e., λij>1\lambda_{ij} > 1. Tan et al. (Stat. Med., 2025) extend signal estimation: estimate {λij}\{\lambda_{ij}\} quantify uncertainty via flexible nonparametric empirical Bayes posterior distribution. Signal estimation helps distinguish AE-drug pairs look identical binary signal detection framework (e.g., () vs ()), can substantially different clinical implications. Methods implemented pvEBayes (differ prior assumptions): Gamma-Poisson Shrinker (GPS) Koenker–Mizera method (KM) Efron’s nonparametric empirical Bayes approach K-gamma method General-gamma method nonparametric priors? GPS uses 2 gamma mixture prior motivated signal/non-signal structure. Real-world signal strengths (_{ij}) can heterogeneous multi-modal, making simple parametric priors hard justify. Nonparametric empirical Bayes methods (KM, Efron, general-gamma) address challenge utilizing flexible prior general mixture form estimating prior distribution data-driven way. Implementation highlights: Provides fully open-source KM implementation using CVXR (avoids reliance commercial Mosek solver used REBayes). Adapts Efron’s approach deconvolveR support exposure/offset (E_{ij}) Poisson model (supported original implementation) . Implements bi-level Expectation Conditional Maximization (ECM) algorithm Tan et al. (Stat. Med., 2025) prior estimation gamma-mixture prior based models (GPS, K-gamma, general-gamma). detailed methodological description, see Tan et al.  (Stat. Med., 2025).

title: Fit a general-gamma, GPS, K-gamma, KM or efron model for a contingency table. — pvEBayes
text: contin_table IxJ contingency table showing pairwise counts adverse events AEs (along rows) J drugs (along columns). model model fit. Available models "general-gamma", "K-gamma", "GPS", "KM" "efron". Default "general-gamma". Note input model case-sensitive. alpha numeric 0 1. hyperparameter "general-gamma" model. needed "general-gamma" model used. Small 'alpha' encourages shrinkage mixture weights estimated prior distribution. See Tan et al. (2025) details. K integer greater equal 2 indicating number mixture components prior distribution. needed "K-gamma" model used. See Tan et al. (2025) details. p integer greater equal 2. needed "efron" mode used. Larger p leads smoother estimated prior distribution. See Narasimhan Efron (2020) detail. c0 numeric greater 0. needed "efron" mode used. Large c0 encourage estimated prior distribution shrink toward discrete uniform. See Narasimhan Efron (2020) detail. maxi upper limit iteration ECM algorithm. tol_ecm tolerance parameter used ECM stopping rule, defined absolute change joint marginal likelihood two consecutive iterations. used 'GPS', 'K-gamma' 'general-gamma' model fitted. Default 1e-4. rtol_efron tolerance parameter used 'efron' model fitted. Default 1e-10. See 'stats::nlminb' detail. rtol_KM tolerance parameter used 'KM' model fitted. Default 1e-6. See 'CVXR::solve' detail. n_posterior_draws number posterior draws AE-drug combination. E matrix expected counts null model SRS frequency table. NULL (default), expected counts estimated SRS data using 'estimate_null_expected_count()'.

title: Fit a general-gamma, GPS, K-gamma, KM or efron model for a contingency table. — pvEBayes
text: function implements ECM algorithm proposed Tan et al. (2025), providing stable efficient implementation Gamma-Poisson Shrinker(GPS), K-gamma "general-gamma" methods signal estimation signal detection Spontaneous Reporting System (SRS) data table. Method "GPS" proposed DuMouchel (1999) parametric empirical Bayes model two gamma mixture prior distribution. Methods "K-gamma" "general-gamma" non-parametric empirical Bayes models, introduced Tan et al. (2025). number mixture components "K" needs prespecified fitting "K-gamma" model. "general-gamma", mixture weights regularized Dirichlet hyper prior hyperparameter \(0 \leq \alpha < 1\) controls shrinkage strength. "alpha" approaches 0, less non-empty mixture components exist fitted model. \(\alpha = 0\), Dirichlet distribution improper prior still offering reasonable posterior inference represents strongest shrinkage "general-gamma" model. Parameter estimation "KM" model formulated convex optimization problem. objective function constraints follow construction REBayes. Parameter estimation performed using open-source convex optimization package CVXR. implementation "efron" model package adapted deconvolveR package, developed Bradley Efron Balasubramanian Narasimhan. original implementation deconvolveR support exposure offset parameter Poisson model, corresponds expected null value (\(E_{ij}\)) AE-drug combination. address , modified relevant code allow inclusion \(E_{ij}\) Poisson likelihood. addition, implemented method estimating degrees freedom, enabling AIC- BIC-based hyperparameter selection "efron" model (Tan et al. 2025). See pvEBayes_tune details.

title: Fit a general-gamma, GPS, K-gamma, KM or efron model for a contingency table. — pvEBayes
code: set.seed(1) ref_table <- statin2025_44  # set up signal matrix with one signal at entry (1,1) sig_mat <- matrix(1, nrow(ref_table), ncol(ref_table)) sig_mat[c(1, 5), 1] <- 2   simu_table <- generate_contin_table(   ref_table = ref_table,   signal_mat = sig_mat,   n_table = 1 )[[1]]   # fit general-gamma model with a specified alpha fit <- pvEBayes(   contin_table = simu_table,   model = "general-gamma",   alpha = 0.3,   n_posterior_draws = 1000,   E = NULL,   maxi = NULL )  # fit K-gamma model with K = 3 fit_Kgamma <- pvEBayes(   contin_table = simu_table, model = "K-gamma",   K = 3, n_posterior_draws = 1000 )   # fit Efron model with specified hyperparameters # p = 40, c0 = 0.05  if (FALSE) { # \dontrun{ fit_efron <- pvEBayes(   contin_table = simu_table,   model = "efron",   p = 40,   c0 = 0.05,   n_posterior_draws = 1000 ) } # }  # fit GPS model and comapre with 'openEBGM'   fit_gps <- pvEBayes(simu_table, model = "GPS")  if (FALSE) { # \dontrun{  ## Optional comparison with openEBGM (only if installed)  ## tol_ecm is the absolute tolerance for ECM stopping rule. ## It is set to ensure comparability to `openEBGM`.  fit_gps <- pvEBayes(simu_table, model = "GPS", tol_ecm = 1e-2)  if (requireNamespace("openEBGM", quietly = TRUE)) {   E <- estimate_null_expected_count(simu_table)   simu_table_stacked <- as.data.frame(as.table(simu_table))   simu_table_stacked$E <- as.vector(E)   colnames(simu_table_stacked) <- c("var1", "var2", "N", "E")   simu_table_stacked_squash <- openEBGM::autoSquash(simu_table_stacked)    hyper_estimates <- openEBGM::hyperEM(simu_table_stacked_squash,     theta_init = c(2, 1, 2, 2, 0.2),     method = "nlminb",     N_star = NULL,     zeroes = TRUE,     param_upper = Inf,     LL_tol = 1e-2,     max_iter = 10000   ) }  theta_hat <- hyper_estimates$estimates qn <- openEBGM::Qn(theta_hat,   N = simu_table_stacked$N,   E = simu_table_stacked$E )  simu_table_stacked$q05 <- openEBGM::quantBisect(5,   theta_hat = theta_hat,   N = simu_table_stacked$N,   E = simu_table_stacked$E,   qn = qn )  ## obtain the detected signal provided by openEBGM simu_table_stacked %>%   subset(q05 > 1.001)  ## detected signal from pvEBayes presented in the same way as openEBGM fit_gps %>%   summary(return = "posterior draws") %>%   apply(c(2, 3), quantile, prob = 0.05) %>%   as.table() %>%   as.data.frame() %>%   subset(Freq > 1.001) } # }
